comments.commentBody:
@Ordinary Jen: I would suggest that you read the transcript just above yours. It is arguable about the efficacy of, and even the feasibility of deporting illegal aliens. But it would be EASY to find and punish the employers who hire them. I am a chef, and I have worked in many restaurants that hire illegal aliens. Everybody but an idiot (or the IRS or INS) would be able to figure out that  restaurant with $10K+ a week in documentable credit card revenue would require more than $1000 in reportable payroll, the salaries of the two owners removed from the equation.<br/>
When Alabama passed a "show me your papers" law last year, the unintended consequence was that millions of dollars worth of produce rotted in the fields. The farmers were unwilling or unable to hire local citizens or legal aliens to do the stoop labor required to harvest.<br/>
My experience in restaurants tells me that illegal aliens are more motivated, more reliable workers who do not approach their jobs with an inherent sense of entitlement. THEY are the people who will be the next class of restaurateurs and other entrepreneurs. Deporting them will solve NOTHING; it will create unintended harm to the economy, as it did in Alabama.
